---
import Landing from '../layouts/Landing.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import { ContentSchema } from '../content/config';
import contentJson from '../content.example.json';

const content = ContentSchema.parse(contentJson);
---
<Landing content={content} pageTitle={`Launching ${content.project.name}`}>
  <article class="prose dark:prose-invert">
    <h1>Launching {content.project.name}</h1>
    <div data-testid="launch-post-body">

      {/* Section 1: Implementer's fictional draft — Aiden rewrites with the real moment before publishing. */}
      <h2>Why I built this</h2>
      <p>
        A few weeks ago I was sketching out a multi-agent flow where the agent on one side of a
        handoff was running in one framework and the agent on the other side was running in another.
        The framework-specific registries each side used couldn't see each other. There wasn't a
        portable thing one agent could hand to the other to say "here's what I am and here's how to
        reach me, verify this signature yourself."
      </p>
      <p>
        I looked at A2A and AGNTCY. Both have answers for the communication layer once two agents are
        already pointed at each other. Neither pins down a portable, signed, verifiable agent manifest
        that an agent in framework A can publish for an agent in framework B to consume without a
        central registry. The closest prior art I found was DID documents (W3C) and OpenID Connect
        Discovery — both close in spirit, neither shaped right for agents that announce capabilities.
      </p>
      <p>
        I wrote down what that manifest would have to look like for me to use it on both sides, plus
        the matching algorithm a consumer would run locally. <code>p2p-agent-discovery</code> is that
        spec, with a reference CLI that demonstrates the full cycle: keygen, manifest create, manifest
        verify, discover.
      </p>

      <h2>What's broken today</h2>
      <p>
        Each framework manages its own agents internally. LangChain, AutoGen, and CrewAI all have
        internal registries that don't speak to each other. Each marketplace maintains its own
        catalog. When an agent in framework A needs to invoke an agent in framework B, there is no
        portable wire format both sides can produce and consume — no signed document one agent can
        hand to another that says "here is what I do and here is how to verify I'm who I claim to be."
      </p>
      <p>
        The prior art closest in spirit is W3C DID documents and OpenID Connect Discovery. DID
        documents are self-sovereign identity records that carry verification methods and service
        endpoints — the right shape in principle, but designed for human identity and the broader
        DID ecosystem, which brings in JSON-LD contexts, DID methods, and resolver infrastructure
        that agents don't need. OIDC Discovery is a well-proven pattern for capability advertisement,
        but it's tied to the OAuth/OIDC stack and assumes a central authorization server. Neither is
        the right shape for a lightweight, framework-neutral agent manifest that any consumer can
        verify locally with nothing but a public key.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is that agent discovery today is registry-specific by default — which means every
        framework reinvents it, every marketplace creates a new silo, and agents can't find each
        other across org boundaries without a pre-arranged business relationship.
      </p>

      <h2>Spec walkthrough</h2>
      <p>
        The spec defines four concepts. The first is the <strong>Agent Manifest</strong>: a signed
        JSON document containing a <code>publisher</code> block (an Ed25519 public key and a
        fingerprint derived from it), a <code>capabilities</code> array (each capability has a name,
        version, parameter schema, and tags), an <code>endpoints</code> array (transport-agnostic —
        HTTP, gRPC, or any other scheme), and an <code>expires_at</code> timestamp. A manifest is
        self-contained: everything a consumer needs to verify it and decide whether to use it is
        inside the document itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second is the <strong>Discovery Query</strong>: a JSON document that specifies which
        capability to look for, a set of constraints on capability fields (supporting operators
        <code>eq</code>, <code>ne</code>, <code>gt</code>, <code>gte</code>, <code>lt</code>,
        <code>lte</code>, <code>contains</code>, and <code>in</code>), and an optional ranking
        definition (a list of path/direction/weight triples).
      </p>
      <p>
        The third is the <strong>matching algorithm</strong>: filter manifests by capability name,
        apply each constraint, score surviving manifests by summing the weighted ranking terms, sort
        by score descending then by <code>manifest_id</code> ascending for tie-breaking. The algorithm
        is fully deterministic — same inputs, same ranked list, every time.
      </p>
      <p>
        The fourth is the <strong>signature scheme</strong>: Ed25519 over the canonical JSON
        serialization of the manifest body (RFC 8785 JCS — all object keys sorted recursively before
        hashing). The <code>publisher.id</code> field is the string{' '}
        <code>ed25519:&lt;11-char base64url SHA-256 prefix&gt;</code>, giving a stable human-readable
        fingerprint. Full details in{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/Accuoa/p2p-agent-discovery/blob/main/SPEC.md">SPEC.md</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>The numbers</h2>
      <p>
        The benchmark runs 30 hand-built fixtures across six categories: 5 simple capability matches,
        5 ranking exercises, 5 filter-constraint cases, 5 contains-operator cases, 5 expiry-boundary
        cases, and 5 empty-result cases. Every fixture is labeled; expected output is declared
        alongside input. The scorer is deterministic: given the same manifest directory and query, it
        always returns the same ranked list.
      </p>
      <p>
        Network footprint is audited rather than mocked. The benchmark wraps the Node.js{' '}
        <code>http</code> and <code>https</code> modules and logs every outbound call to{' '}
        <code>logs/network.jsonl</code>. The final assertion is that the file is empty. It is.
        Determinism is verified by running the engine three times with identical inputs and comparing
        outputs byte-for-byte. All three runs produce identical results. Output from the current run:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`[p2p-agent-discovery] running benchmark — 30 fixtures

  loading fixtures...   30/30 OK
  matching...           30/30 OK

FIDELITY:
  simple (5):           5/5 (100.0%)
  ranking (5):          5/5 (100.0%)
  filter (5):           5/5 (100.0%)
  contains (5):         5/5 (100.0%)
  expiry (5):           5/5 (100.0%)
  empty (5):            5/5 (100.0%)

  total:                30/30 (100.0%)

NETWORK FOOTPRINT:
  external calls:  0
  audit log:       ./logs/network.jsonl

STATUS: Strong band`}</code></pre>
      <p>
        "Strong band" is the benchmark's top classification. It requires 100% fidelity across all
        six categories, zero external calls, and three byte-identical runs. Calibration
        SHA-256:{' '}<code>7C0BF8021A4FC922F4594523202522A917CC963CBB660DE2016F98DC8DB2D8D7</code>.
        The 30-fixture count is honest — it is not a massive corpus. But the methodology is: every
        fixture is hand-built, every category is labeled, the output is deterministic, and you can
        reproduce it with nothing beyond <code>node</code>.
      </p>

      <h2>Try it</h2>
      <pre><code>{`p2pad keygen alice
p2pad manifest create draft.json alice.priv > manifest.json
p2pad manifest verify manifest.json
p2pad discover query.json manifests/`}</code></pre>
      <p>
        Or run the full cycle in one command from the repo root:
      </p>
      <pre><code>bash full-cycle.sh</code></pre>
      <p>
        <code>full-cycle.sh</code> installs dependencies, runs the test suite (67/67), runs the
        benchmark (30/30), and runs calibration. Expected final output: Strong band, SHA-256
        matching the locked value above.
      </p>

      <h2>Limitations</h2>
      <p>
        The spec deliberately omits several things that are out of scope for v0.1. There is no
        transport implementation — the spec says nothing about how manifests are distributed (mDNS,
        DHT, gossip, or any other mechanism are all valid; none are specified). There is no shared
        capability taxonomy: capability names are free-form strings, so two publishers can use
        different names for the same thing. There is no key rotation or revocation mechanism. There
        are no query joins (a single query targets one capability name), no regex constraints, and no
        integration of Plan 8 (agent-reputation) attestation refs on the wire. These are tracked
        in{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/Accuoa/p2p-agent-discovery/blob/main/OPEN_QUESTIONS.md">OPEN_QUESTIONS.md</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What's next</h2>
      <p>
        Plan 9 composes directly with Plan 8. Discovery finds an agent by what it claims to do;
        agent-reputation tells you whether to trust it. The two specs are designed to chain: run
        discovery to get a ranked list of candidates, query the reputation store for attestations
        about the top candidates, then decide which one to invoke.
      </p>
      <p>
        Likely v0.2 candidates: an optional <code>taxonomy_ref</code> field on capabilities (to
        anchor capability names to a shared vocabulary), an <code>attestation_refs</code> field on
        the manifest (linking to agent-reputation attestations), and transport hints. Weigh in on
        priorities in{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/Accuoa/p2p-agent-discovery/blob/main/OPEN_QUESTIONS.md">OPEN_QUESTIONS.md</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Where to find me</h2>
      <p>
        GitHub: <a href="https://github.com/Accuoa">@Accuoa</a> — the repo and issues live here.<br />
        Twitter/X: <a href="https://twitter.com/aidenbolin">@aidenbolin</a> — launch thread and updates.<br />
        dev.to: <a href="https://dev.to/accuoa">@accuoa</a> — longer write-ups cross-posted here.
      </p>

    </div>
  </article>
</Landing>
<SiteFooter content={content} />
